loading_protocol:
1. A set of ramp-up table motions were generated using an analytical procedure in order to achieve the target motions on the desired levels.
2. These levels were the second floor, for the first seven motions of the linear tests, and the shake table for other cases (nonlinear tests and the last two motions of linear tests).
3. The AC156 spectrum with the maximum parameters of ARIG-H=2.0g, AFLX-H=4.0g, SDS=2.5g, and z/h=0.5 was considered as the target spectrum for the full-scale motion. In total, 59 uniaxial motions were applied in longitudinal direction during eight experiments
design_objective: investigate the system-level response and failure mechanisms of nonstructural systems. All walls were designed per ASTM C754-11
comp_description:
1. 5/8-in. gypsum boards and the CEMCO ViperStud drywall framing system (350VS125-18/30 and 350VT125-18/30).
2. Studs were located 24 in. apart, attached to the gypsum boards by #6 drywall screws spaced 12 in. in the field and 8 in. at boundaries
3. Partition wall tracks were fastened to concrete slabs using 0.157-in diameter, fully knurled shank Hilti X-U Universal Powder-Actuated Fasteners (PAFs).
4. All walls were designed per ASTM C754-11
5. Full connection: steel studs scred to runners, gypsum boards attached to runners and steel studs
6. Stud thickness 25 Ga.
ds_description: Popping out or rocking of gypsum board screws

design_objective: investigate the system-level response and failure mechanisms of nonstructural systems. All walls were designed per ASTM C754-12
comp_description:
1. 5/8-in. gypsum boards and the CEMCO ViperStud drywall framing system (350VS125-18/30 and 350VT125-18/30).

loading_protocol:
The protocol is a modified version of that developed by Krawinkler et al. for wood frame  construction in far-fault regions. It consisted of 
1. one-cycle to a drift of 0.05% followed by three cycles to a drift of 0.1% ,0.3%, 0.5%, 1%, and 1.5%. 
2. Then, in recognition that the number of large amplitude cycles is lesser than those of smaller amplitude, a single cycle was applied to 2% drift , followed by two trailing cycles to 1% drift.
3. Testing continued by applying a single cycle to 3% drift, followed by trailing two cycles to 1.5% drift . 
4. Testing ended with the application of a single cycle to 3.5% inter story drift.
design_objective: common United States practice:
comp_description:
1. Full board sheathing
2. Each specimen consisted of a 4.88m long web wall and two return walls each 1.2m long
3. The Power Driven Fasteners were placed at 812mm intervals
4. The studs were sheathed onbothsides with interior and fire-rated Type X  gypsumboards manufactured in accordance to ASTMC1396
5. Self-drilling screw spacing = 204 mm
6. Gypsum board thickness = 16 mm
7. Metal stud gage = 25 
8. Stud spacing = 610 mm
9. Gypsym board height = 2.44 m
ds_description: minor tape uplift and paint cracking at the joints in the door header gypsum wallboard.

1. one-cycle to a drift of 0.05% followed by three cycles to a drift of 0.1% ,0.3%, 0.5%, 1%, and 1.5%. 
2. Then, in recognition that the number of large amplitude cycles is lesser than those of smaller amplitude, a single cycle was applied to 2% drift , followed by two trailing cycles to 1% drift.
3. Testing continued by applying a single cycle to 3% drift, followed by trailing two cycles to 1.5% drift . 
4. Testing ended with the application of a single cycle to 3.5% inter story drift.
design_objective: common United States practice:
comp_description:
1. Full board sheathing
2. Each specimen consisted of a 4.88m long web wall and two return walls each 1.2m long
3. The Power Driven Fasteners were placed at 812mm intervals
4. The studs were sheathed onbothsides with interior and fire-rated Type X  gypsumboards manufactured in accordance to ASTMC1396
5. Self-drilling screw spacing = 204 mm
6. Gypsum board thickness = 16 mm
7. Metal stud gage = 25 
8. Stud spacing = 610 mm
9. Gypsym board height = 2.44 m

notes: If ds_class = unknown then sufficient description of the damage or photo is unavailable to make a decision

The protocol is a modified version of that developed by Krawinkler et al. for wood frame  construction in far-fault regions. It consisted of 
1. one-cycle to a drift of 0.05% followed by three cycles to a drift of 0.1% ,0.3%, 0.5%, 1%, and 1.5%. 
2. Then, in recognition that the number of large amplitude cycles is lesser than those of smaller amplitude, a single cycle was applied to 2% drift , followed by two trailing cycles to 1% drift.
3. Testing continued by applying a single cycle to 3% drift, followed by trailing two cycles to 1.5% drift . 
4. Testing ended with the application of a single cycle to 3.5% inter story drift.

comp_description:
RESTRAINED and WELDED Assembly
Two water heaters (attached to shake table), one heat exchanger (atatched to shake table), three riser branches, and horizontal runs.
The piping assembly consists of 3in (out dia=3.5 in, thickness=0.216 in) and 4 in (out dia=4.5 in, thickness=0.237 in) schedule 40 ASTM A53 Grade B black steel pipe
Water heater connected to 3 in file through four-bolt flanged connection
Heat Exhanger and all valves connected to 4 in pipe through eght-bolt flanged connection
Hydrostatic pressure
1/8 in dia galvanized 7 no.s of strands x19 wires per strand aircraft grade steel (with min break strength of 1700lbs) Cable restrainers used as seismic bracing
5/8 in dia all threaded rods for 4-in pipes
1/2 in dia all threaded rods for 3-in pipes
Vertical hanger rods braced laterally along their length with a 1  5/8 in sq, 12 gauge strut to prevent buckling
cross bolts in hanger clevises
Welded assemblies (Root material E6010 and fill material E7018). Each joint was prepared with a 65o, 3/32-in root and 3/32-in landing.
ds_description: Flanged connection joining the heat exchanger to the pipe began to leak (100% IM)
notes: Maximum measured acceleration on pipes = 2.5g

comp_description:
The top level was designed to evaluate the seismic behavior of an unsupported elbow armover, a cross main line, as well as longitudinal and transverse branch lines. 
The bottom level was designed to assess the performance of a longitudinal main line and longer transverse branch lines subjected to earthquake shaking.
a total of six generic ceiling boxes supporting ceiling tiles were installed at various locations to assess potential failure mechanisms of sprinkler heads interacting with the suspended ceiling during earthquake shaking
The two levels of the specimen were connected together by a vertical riser
Main Line, Cross Main, and Vertical Riser: 10.2-cm steel pipes (schedule 10) with groove-fit connections (4 in pipes)
Flexible couplings were installed within 30.5 cm above and below the simulated floor slab.
pressure = 40 psi
10 mm hanger rods, 12g wire restrainers
Branch lines = black iron pipes (schedule 40) with threaded connections (2 in pipes)
Fully braced specimen (bracing systems installed according to NFPA 13. (1 in dia pipe braces and wire restrainers next at the ends of cantilever pipes on top level (no end pipe bracings on bottom floor)
ds_description: No damage (100% MCE)
notes:
1. First mode natural frequency = 1.74 Hz
2. Damping = 8.7% of critical damping
3. Max acceleration recorded = 3.69g at the end of branch line
PFA as damage state intensity

The bottom level was designed to assess the performance of a longitudinal main line and longer transverse branch lines subjected to earthquake shaking.
a total of six generic ceiling boxes supporting ceiling tiles were installed at various locations to assess potential failure mechanisms of sprinkler heads interacting with the suspended ceiling during earthquake shaking
The two levels of the specimen were connected together by a vertical riser
Main Line, Cross Main, and Vertical Riser: 10.2-cm steel pipes (schedule 10) with groove-fit connections (4 in pipes)
Flexible couplings were installed within 30.5 cm above and below the simulated floor slab.
pressure = 40 psi
10 mm hanger rods, 12g wire restrainers
Branch lines = Schedule 7 Dyna-Flow steel pipes with groove-fit connections (2 in pipes)
Fully unbraced specimen
ds_description: Two branch lines leaked at the connections with the main run (100% MCE)
notes:
Max acceleration recorded = 5.037g at the end of branch line
PFA as damage state intensity

loading_protocol: Spectral accelerations SDS=1 g and SD1=0.6 g, and a maximum inter-story drift ratio 3%
peak_test_amplitude: intensity of input motions for both platforms was increased from 25%, 50%, 66.7% (Design DE level), to 100% (MCE level)
location: University at Buffalo Nonstructural Component Simulator (UB-NCS)

test_type: Uniaxial shake table (ground) motions that were artificially generated by using a spectrum-matching procedure
loading_protocol:
Parameters from the AC 156 [ICC, 2010] including, a story height ratio (z/h) of 0.5 and the design spectral 
response acceleration at short periods (SDS) of 2.5 g, were used to develop two targeted acceleration spectrum
location:
University of Nevada, Reno Network for Earthquake Engineering Simulation
site
comp_description:
Pressure = 50 psi
Riser pipe = 4 in diameter
Branch pipe= 2 in diameter (update if necessary)
armovers=1 in diameter
Plenum depth varied from 12 in to 22 in
Hangers = 10mm (3/8 in) dia threaded rods
Braces = 1 in schedule 40 pipes oriented at 45 degrees
Wire restrainers(splay wires) = 12 g wires @ 45 degrees
Braces and Wire restrainers connected to concrete deck through 10 mm (3/8 in) Hilti KB-TZ expansion anchors
The gap between the sprinkler hed and ceiling tile was either 2 in or no gap. 
The ceiling system looks like braced.
ds_description: Hanger band slip/drift along pipe
notes:
1. Maximum Peak Floor Acceleration as Damage Intensity Measure
2. Maximum inter story drift 2.09%
3. Median pipe joint rotation = 0.001-0.013 radians
4. Maximum measured axial load for hangers=1.26 Kips and wire restrainers=0.34 kips

loading_protocol:
static cyclic loading test was conducted ten times using a sine wave for the allowable side sway as per the ASCE 7–16 for all structures,
Loading control: Displacement control 
Loading cycles: Sinusoidal, 10 cycles
Loading displacement: ± 60 mm,
Loading velocity: 20 mm/min
comp_description:
Height of the pipe system = 3 m (9.84 ft)
Vertical pipe system with two-90 degree elbows and one Tee joint
Outer diamater = 100mm (4")
Pipe connections were located within 305 mm (1 ft ) from the floor and 610 mm (2 ft) from the ceiling.
the distance between riser pipe and a 4-way brace is within 7.6 m.
Specimen SP01 with Pressure joints (used in Korea)
Pipe material SUS 304 (KS D 3595) with:
Elastic Modulus = 193000 MPa
Poisson's ratio = 0.29
Yield Strength = 283 MPa
Tensile Strength = 631 MPa
Elongation  = 56 %
Water pressure = 2 Mpa ( 290 psi)
RISER
ds_description: The visual inspection performed after the test showed no external deformation, water leak, crack, component separation, and damage in the test specimens.
notes: Interstory drift as DSI

design_objective: Evaluate the seismic response and fragilities of drywall partition walls
comp_description:
1. The indoor partition wall is surrounded by structural elements on all sides
2. Wall dimensions: 2400 mm Long, 2700 mm High, and 125 mm Thick
3. Lightweight steel profiles: 
- Steel grade (DX51D+Z), 
- Studs (75mmx50mmx7.5mmx0.6mm) - (outside‐to‐outside web depth × outside‐to‐outside flange size × outside‐to‐outside lip size × thickness), 
- Tracks 75 × 40 × 0.6 mm (outside‐to‐outside web depth × outside‐to‐outside flange size × thickness) unlipped channel sections
4. Stud spacing: 600 mm
5. Sheathing panels: Double layer of 12.5‐mm‐thick standard gypsum boards for each wall face
6. Frame fixings: Punching
7. Panel-to-frame fixings: 
- 3.5 × 25 mm (nominal diameter × shank length) bugle head phosphated self‐piercing screws spaced at
700 mm on center for the installation of the internal panel laye, 
- 3.5 × 35‐mm bugle head phosphated self‐piercing screws spaced at 250 mm on center for the installation
of the external panel layer
8. Joint finishing: 
- Joints in the field: Glass fiber tape with an alkaline‐resistant coating fixed with gypsumbased plaster
- Joints at the perimeter : Glass fiber tape with an alkaline‐resistant coating fixed with gypsumbased plaster
9. Wall‐to‐surrounding structural element connections: 6 × 35 mm (drilling hole diameter × minimum anchorage length) plastic dowels for fixed connections or 8 × 80‐mm plastic dowels for sliding connections, spaced at 500 mm on center at the wall top and bottom and 600 mm on center at the wall ends
10. Horizontal connection: Fixed
11. Vertical connection: Fixed
ds_description: Drop of gypsum dust

comp_description:
1. The indoor partition wall is connected at its ends with transversal outdoor façade walls, top and bottom with structure
2. Wall dimensions: 2400 mm Long, 2700 mm High, and 125 mm Thick
3. Lightweight steel profiles: 
- Steel grade (DX51D+Z), 
- Studs (75mmx50mmx7.5mmx0.6mm) - (outside‐to‐outside web depth × outside‐to‐outside flange size × outside‐to‐outside lip size × thickness), 
- Tracks 75 × 40 × 0.6 mm (outside‐to‐outside web depth × outside‐to‐outside flange size × thickness) unlipped channel sections
4. Stud spacing: 600 mm
5. Sheathing panels: Double layer of 12.5‐mm‐thick standard gypsum boards for each wall face
6. Frame fixings: Punching
7. Panel-to-frame fixings: 
- 3.5 × 25 mm (nominal diameter × shank length) bugle head phosphated self‐piercing screws spaced at
700 mm on center for the installation of the internal panel laye, 
- 3.5 × 35‐mm bugle head phosphated self‐piercing screws spaced at 250 mm on center for the installation
of the external panel layer
8. Joint finishing: 
- Joints in the field: paper tape fixed with gypsum‐based plaster
- Joints at the perimeter : self‐adhesive paper tape
9. Wall‐to‐surrounding structural element connections: 6 × 35 mm (drilling hole diameter × minimum anchorage length) plastic dowels for fixed connections or 8 × 80‐mm plastic dowels for sliding connections, spaced at 500 mm on center at the wall top and bottom and 600 mm on center at the wall ends
10. Horizontal connection: Sliding
ds_description: Local plastic deformations of studs

loading_protocol: The quasi-static testing protocol was developed for evaluating the seismic fragility of primarily driftsensitive components. The amplitude modulation is based on a dynamic loading protocol developed for each level of the UB-NCS that can simultaneously match (1) a target floor response spectrum (FRS) and (2) either a target generalized interstory drift (GID) or a maximum interstory drift, Dmax (Retamales et al. 2008, 2011). Maximum amplitude: +-3%
design_objective: To evaluate the seismic response, failure mechanisms, and fragilities of cold-formed steel framed gypsum partition walls.
comp_description:
1. The partition wall specimens were approximately 3,660 mm (12 ft) long by 3,500 mm (11.5 ft) tall.
2. The I-shapedwall with 600-mm-length (2-ft-length) return walls at each end 
3. Spacing of track fasteners to slabs of  24 in. on center.
5. studs and gypsum wallboards were not screwed to the top track: slip track
6. Full height partition wall
7. Gypsum wallboard connected to bottom track
8. Spacing of steel studs of 400 or 600 mm (16 or 24 in.) on center
9. In-plane
10. 350S125-18 studs and used tracks of similar thickness.
11. A single ply of 15-mm-thick (5/8-in.-thick) gypsum board was used for the walls with each sheet having a stock size of 1,200 x2,400 mm (4x 8 ft)
12. Finished with metal corner beads and drywall paper joint tape
ds_description: Cracks along tape/pulled tape/crushing wall vertical edges

loading_protocol: The quasi-static testing protocol was developed for evaluating the seismic fragility of primarily driftsensitive components. The amplitude modulation is based on a dynamic loading protocol developed for each level of the UB-NCS that can simultaneously match (1) a target floor response spectrum (FRS) and (2) either a target generalized interstory drift (GID) or a maximum interstory drift, Dmax (Retamales et al. 2008, 2011). Maximum amplitude: +-3%
design_objective: To evaluate the seismic response, failure mechanisms, and fragilities of cold-formed steel framed gypsum partition walls.
comp_description:
1. The partition wall specimens were approximately 3,660 mm (12 ft) long by 3,500 mm (11.5 ft) tall.
2. The I-shapedwall with 600-mm-length (2-ft-length) return walls at each end 
3. Spacing of track fasteners to slabs of  24 in. on center.
4. Presence of transverse (return) walls
5. studs and gypsum wallboards were not screwed to the top track: slip track
6. Full height partition wall
7. Gypsum wallboard connected to bottom track
8. Spacing of steel studs of 400 or 600 mm (16 or 24 in.) on center
9. In-plane
10. 350S125-18 studs and used tracks of similar thickness.
11. A single ply of 15-mm-thick (5/8-in.-thick) gypsum board was used for the walls with each sheet having a stock size of 1,200 x2,400 mm (4x 8 ft)
12. Finished with metal corner beads and drywall paper joint tape
ds_description: Cracks along tape/pulled tape/crushing wall vertical edges

The amplitude modulation is based on a dynamic loading protocol developed for each level of the UB-NCS that can simultaneously match (1) a target floor response spectrum (FRS) and (2) either a target generalized interstory drift (GID) or a maximum interstory drift, Dmax (Retamales et al. 2008, 2011). Maximum amplitude: +-3%
design_objective: To evaluate the seismic response, failure mechanisms, and fragilities of cold-formed steel framed gypsum partition walls.
comp_description:
1. The partition wall specimens were partial -height seismically braced following Gypsum Association GA-50 standard. Walls height 8ft.
2.  The I-shapedwall with 600-mm-length (2-ft-length) return walls at each end 
3. Spacing of track fasteners to slabs of  24 in. on center.
4. Presence of transverse (return) walls
5. studs and gypsum wallboards were not screwed to the top track: slip track
6. Full height partition wall
7. Gypsum wallboard connected to bottom and top  track
8. Spacing of steel studs of 24 in.) on center. 
9. In-plane
10. 350S125-18 studs and used tracks of similar thickness. 25G steel frame. 
11. A single ply of 15-mm-thick (5/8-in.-thick) gypsum board was used for the walls with each sheet having a stock size of 1,200 x2,400 mm (4x 8 ft)
12. Finished with metal corner beads and drywall paper joint tape
13. Stud connected to bottom and top track (Full connection)
ds_description: Brace buckling/top track bending

 2. The I-shapedwall with 600-mm-length (2-ft-length) return walls at each end 
 3. Spacing of track fasteners to slabs of 24 in. on center.
 4. Stud to bottom track connection
 5. studs and gypsum wallboards were not screwed to the top track: slip track
 6. Full height partition wall
 7. Gypsum wallboard connected to bottom track only
 8. Spacing of steel studs of 16 in.on center
 9. In-plane
 10. 350S125-30 studs and used tracks of similar thickness. 20G steel
 11. A single ply of 15-mm-thick (5/8-in.-thick) gypsum board was used for the walls with each sheet having a stock size of 1,200 x2,400 mm (4x 8 ft)
 12. Finished with metal corner beads and drywall paper joint tape
 13. Institutional construction details (top track to slip horizontally)
 14. screw spacing 8" in the perimenter of the walls

 2. The I-shapedwall with 600-mm-length (2-ft-length) return walls at each end 
 3. Spacing of track fasteners to slabs of 24 in. on center.
 4. Stud to bottom track connection
 5. studs and gypsum wallboards were not screwed to the top track: slip track
 6. Full height partition wall
 7. Gypsum wallboard connected to bottom track only
 8. Spacing of steel studs of 16 in.on center
 9. In-plane
 10. 350S125-30 studs and used tracks of similar thickness. 20G steel
 11. A single ply of 15-mm-thick (5/8-in.-thick) gypsum board was used for the walls with each sheet having a stock size of 1,200 x2,400 mm (4x 8 ft)
 12. Finished with metal corner beads and drywall paper joint tape
 13. Institutional construction details (top track to slip horizontally)
 14. screw spacing 8" in the perimenter of the walls
ds_description: Damage in gypsumboard transverse wall
proir_damage: Cracks along tape/pulled tape/crushing wall vertical edges

loading_protocol: The quasi-static testing protocol was developed for evaluating the seismic fragility of primarily driftsensitive components. The amplitude modulation is based on a dynamic loading protocol developed for each level of the UB-NCS that can simultaneously match (1) a target floor response spectrum (FRS) and (2) either a target generalized interstory drift (GID) or a maximum interstory drift, Dmax (Retamales et al. 2008, 2011). Maximum amplitude: +-3%

loading_protocol: The quasi-static testing protocol was developed for evaluating the seismic fragility of primarily driftsensitive components. The amplitude modulation is based on a dynamic loading protocol developed for each level of the UB-NCS that can simultaneously match (1) a target floor response spectrum (FRS) and (2) either a target generalized interstory drift (GID) or a maximum interstory drift, Dmax (Retamales et al. 2008, 2011). Maximum amplitude: +-3%
design_objective: To evaluate the seismic response, failure mechanisms, and fragilities of cold-formed steel framed gypsum partition walls.
comp_description:
1. The partition wall specimens were approximately 3,660 mm (12 ft) long by 3,500 mm (11.5 ft) tall. 
 2. Having T walll geometries. 
 3. Spacing of track fasteners to slabs of 24 in. on center.
 4. Stud to bottom track connection. Slip track connection
 5. studs and gypsum wallboards were not screwed to the top track: slip track
 6. Full height partition wall
 7. Gypsum wallboard connected to bottom track only
 8. Spacing of steel studs of 24 in.on center
 9. In-plane
 10. 350S125-18 studs and used tracks of similar thickness. 25G steel
 11. A single ply of 15-mm-thick (5/8-in.-thick) gypsum board was used for the walls with each sheet having a stock size of 1,200 x2,400 mm (4x 8 ft)
 12. Finished with metal corner beads and drywall paper joint tape
 13. Improved junction detail: 0.5" gaps at the intersection of perpendicular walls, covered with sacrificial cornerbead attached to the walls using joint
 14. No tracks at the wall intersection. Details proposed for reducing seismic damage
ds_description: Cracks along longitudinal wall corner beads

loading_protocol: quasi-static test protocol provided by FEMA 461
location: laboratory of Stanford University’s John A. Blume Earthquake Engineering Center
design_objective: goal of this research was to improve the seismic performance of interior gypsum partitions and in particular to increase the SDR level at which damage requiring repairs occurs
comp_description:
1. I-shaped gypsum wallboard partitions consisting of a main wall of 2.4 m (8 ft) by 2.4 m (8 ft) connected to two return walls of 1.2 m (4 ft) by 2.4 m (8 ft)
 2. conventional partition
 3. 20 gage cold-formed steel studs spaced 406.4 mm (16 in.) on center attached to 18 gage steel slotted upper tracks and (non-slotted) lower tracks by 12.7 mm (1/2 in.) wafer head screws.
 4. Gypsum wallboard panels with a thickness of 15.9 mm (5/8 in.) were attached to the steel frame with 31.8 mm (1-1/4 in.) coarse threaded drywall screws spaced 203.2 mm (8 in.) on center.
 5. Generic joint compound and 50.8 mm (2 in.) tape were used on the panel joints and corners between the main wall and the return walls.
ds_description: small crack appeared at one intersection between the main wall and one of the return walls

loading_protocol: quasi-static test protocol provided by FEMA 462
location: laboratory of Stanford University’s John A. Blume Earthquake Engineering Center
design_objective: goal of this research was to improve the seismic performance of interior gypsum partitions and in particular to increase the SDR level at which damage requiring repairs occurs
comp_description:
1. I-shaped gypsum wallboard partitions consisting of a main wall of 2.4 m (8 ft) by 2.4 m (8 ft) connected to two return walls of 1.2 m (4 ft) by 2.4 m (8 ft)
 2. Partitions with two new sliding/frictional connections in the main wall (central) and one connection in each return wall, corresponding to one connection every 1.2 m (4 ft).
 3. 20 gage cold-formed steel studs spaced 406.4 mm (16 in.) on center attached to 18 gage steel slotted upper tracks and (non-slotted) lower tracks by 12.7 mm (1/2 in.) wafer head screws.
 4. Gypsum wallboard panels with a thickness of 15.9 mm (5/8 in.) were attached to the steel frame with 31.8 mm (1-1/4 in.) coarse threaded drywall screws spaced 203.2 mm (8 in.) on center.
 5. Generic joint compound and 50.8 mm (2 in.) tape were used on the panel joints and corners between the main wall and the return walls.
 6. The upper track has large circular holes with diameters equivalent to the track’s width (e.g., 88.9 mm) that are centered around two fasteners that attach the short steel tube to the steel plate. These holes accommodate the relative deformations between the upper end of the partition and the floor above the partition.
ds_description: small crack appeared at one intersection between the main wall and one of the return walls

loading_protocol:
Monotonic. At 4% point, the loading was reversed to a peak drift of 4% in the opposite
 direction.
design_objective:
determine the effects of seismic loading on the response
 behavior of gypsum wallboard sheathed walls
comp_description:
1. The walls were all 8 ft. by 16 ft. (2440 mm by 4880 mm) size and framed with 2 in. by 4 in. (50 mm by 100 mm) nominal dimension lumber. All framing lumber was Grade #2 or better, Hem-Fir.
 2. The frames have double top plates, single bottom plates, 4 in. by 4 in. (100 mm by 100mm) endposts and intermediate single studs at 16 in. (406 mm) on center. 
 3. All frames are sheathed on both sides with Standard grade, 1/2-inch (13 mm) gypsum sheathing wallboard. 
 4. The 4x8 foot (1220 mm by 2440 mm) sheathing panels are applied to the wall horizontally.
 5. Fastener : Nails @ 8 in
 6. Constraint at top of wall: Fixed
 7. Wall opening: Door
 8. Method of construction: Floating Edge
ds_description: Cracking of Wallboard at Wall Penetration

loading_protocol: Monotonic. it was desired to know if unloading stiffness could be used as a means of evaluating the remaining strength and stiffness of the wall. To allow for such future study, the applied displacement was reduced at certain points during the test to measure the unloading stiffness. Unloading was performed after photographs were taken at drift levels of 0.75, 1, 1.25, 1.5, 2, and 3% drift.
design_objective:
determine the effects of seismic loading on the response
 behavior of gypsum wallboard sheathed walls
comp_description:
1. The walls were all 8 ft. by 16 ft. (2440 mm by 4880 mm) size and framed with 2 in. by 4 in. (50 mm by 100 mm) nominal dimension lumber. All framing lumber was Grade #2 or better, Hem-Fir.
 2. The frames have double top plates, single bottom plates, 4 in. by 4 in. (100 mm by 100mm) endposts and intermediate single studs at 16 in. (406 mm) on center. 
 3. All frames are sheathed on both sides with Standard grade, 1/2-inch (13 mm) gypsum sheathing wallboard. 
 4. The 4x8 foot (1220 mm by 2440 mm) sheathing panels are applied to the wall horizontally.
 5. Fastener : Nails @ 8 in
 6. Constraint at top of wall: Fixed
 7. Wall opening: Door
 8. Method of construction: Top Sill Fastened

 2. The frames have double top plates, single bottom plates, 4 in. by 4 in. (100 mm by 100mm) endposts and intermediate single studs at 16 in. (406 mm) on center. 
 3. All frames are sheathed on both sides with Standard grade, 1/2-inch (13 mm) gypsum sheathing wallboard. 
 4. The 4x8 foot (1220 mm by 2440 mm) sheathing panels are applied to the wall horizontally.
 5. Fastener : Screws @ 16 in
 6. Constraint at top of wall: Fixed
 7. Wall opening: Door
 8. Method of construction: Floating Edge

 9. Innovative construction method: Type A - to be a cheaper alternative. It used standard wallboard but replaced the standard wallboard screws with screws that had larger heads. Two different screw types were tested, one on the front face and another on the back face. Black-Finish Pan Washer Head (Type A, Phillips Drive, Sharp Point) was one screw tested. These screws were #8 x 1.25 inch long. The other screw tested was Oval Head Phillips with Countersunk Washer (Type A, Sharp Point). These were also #8 x 1.25 inch long.

 2. The frames have double top plates, single bottom plates, 4 in. by 4 in. (100 mm by 100mm) endposts and intermediate single studs at 16 in. (406 mm) on center. 
 3. All frames are sheathed on both sides with Standard grade, 1/2-inch (13 mm) gypsum sheathing wallboard. 
 4. The 4x8 foot (1220 mm by 2440 mm) sheathing panels are applied to the wall horizontally.
 5. Fastener : Screws @ 16 in
 6. Constraint at top of wall: Fixed
 7. Wall opening: Door and Window
 8. Method of construction: Floating Edge
 9. Innovative construction method: Type A - to be a cheaper alternative. It used standard wallboard but replaced the standard wallboard screws with screws that had larger heads. Two different screw types were tested, one on the front face and another on the back face. Black-Finish Pan Washer Head (Type A, Phillips Drive, Sharp Point) was one screw tested. These screws were #8 x 1.25 inch long. The other screw tested was Oval Head Phillips with Countersunk Washer (Type A, Sharp Point). These were also #8 x 1.25 inch long.
ds_description: Cracking of Vertical Out-of-Plane Joint

1. The walls were all 8 ft. by 16 ft. (2440 mm by 4880 mm) size and framed with 2 in. by 4 in. (50 mm by 100 mm) nominal dimension lumber. All framing lumber was Grade #2 or better, Hem-Fir.
 2. The frames have double top plates, single bottom plates, 4 in. by 4 in. (100 mm by 100mm) endposts and intermediate single studs at 16 in. (406 mm) on center. 
 3. All frames are sheathed on both sides with Standard grade, 1/2-inch (13 mm) gypsum sheathing wallboard.

 5. Fastener : Screws @ 16 in
 6. Constraint at top of wall: Fixed
 7. Wall opening: Door and Window
 8. Method of construction: Floating Edge
 9. Innovative construction method: Type B - built with a different type of wallboard. This test was
 intended to represent a more expensive, but higher performing wall than Test #12. Industry
 suppliers suggest that the installed cost of this material is within 20% of standard gypsum wallboard. This was the only specimen tested in the project that did not use Standard 1/2-inch
 gypsum wallboard. FIBERROCK Brand Panels – Abuse Resistant wall material was provided by
 U. S. Gypsum to evaluate if the material would be resistant to damage.

 2. The frames have double top plates, single bottom plates, 4 in. by 4 in. (100 mm by 100mm) endposts and intermediate single studs at 16 in. (406 mm) on center. 
 3. All frames are sheathed on both sides with Standard grade, 1/2-inch (13 mm) gypsum sheathing wallboard. 
 4. The 4x8 foot (1220 mm by 2440 mm) sheathing panels are applied to the wall horizontally.
 5. Fastener : Screws @ 16 in
 6. Constraint at top of wall: Fixed
 7. Wall opening: Door 
 8. Method of construction: Floating Edge

 2. The frames have double top plates, single bottom plates, 4 in. by 4 in. (100 mm by 100mm) endposts and intermediate single studs at 16 in. (406 mm) on center. 
 3. All frames are sheathed on both sides with Standard grade, 1/2-inch (13 mm) gypsum sheathing wallboard. 
 4. The 4x8 foot (1220 mm by 2440 mm) sheathing panels are applied to the wall horizontally.
 5. Fastener : Nails @ 8 in
 6. Constraint at top of wall: Fixed
 7. Wall opening: Door 
 8. Method of construction: Floating Edge
ds_description: Crushing of Wallboard at Perimeter

design_objective: quantifies the onset drifts for different damage thresholds under a unidirectional quasi-static cyclic loading
comp_description:
1.details commonly used to construct interior partition walls in NZ buildings
 2. The specimen tested was oriented oblique to the loading direction and had multiple short wing-walls with one ‘L’-junction (in the west) and one Y-junction (in the east).
 3. 90x45 mm timber runners fastened to concrete slabs using anchor bolts HILTI® HUS3-H8 @ 600 mm c/c in the planar wall, and @430mm c/c in return walls
 4. timber studs (90 mm x 45 mm) were attached at a regular spacing of 600mm c/c to these runners by driving 3 nails at an angle (2 from one side and 1 from the other).
 5. The vertical joint at the south of the Y-junction was reinforced with 135o 0.55BMT (Base Metal Thickness) galvanized steel angles screwed to the studs
 6. A single layer of 13 mm thick gypsum plasterboard was attached to the studs as well as runners using GIB® grabber self-tapping drill point screws (6g x 25 mm) on both sides of the walls.
 7. The spacing between the screws was kept at 300 mm c/c along the boundaries and in the field of the partition wall
 8. the joints were plastered with two coats of GIB® Tradeset 90-minutes premium jointing compound, jointing tape and internal and external corner beads (/L-trims), where necessary.
 9. A final coat of plaster was applied with GIB® Trade Finish.
ds_description: Hairline cracks at joint

seismic performance of “rocking” internal
 partition walls with the dual-slot track (DST) and aluminium angles
comp_description:
1. partition wall specimens (1875 height, 2200 length) comprising DSTs were constructed between parallel concrete slabs. DST is constructed by tek-screwing two different widths of the tracks to provide sufficient slots for the studs and plasterboard to be placed.

 10. Plasterboard screws: GIB® grabber self-tapping drill point screws (6g x 25 mm) @ 150 mm centres.

design_objective:
seismic performance of “rocking” internal
 partition walls with the dual-slot track (DST) and aluminium angles
comp_description:
1. “y” shaped partition wall specimen with the “rocking” connections.
 2. multiple short wing-walls with one “L”-junction (in the west) and one Y-junction (in the east)
 3. The DSTs (68 × 60 × 1 mm track tek-screwed to 100 × 40 × 1 mm track) (see Fig. 14) at the top and bottom of the partition wall were anchored to the concrete slabs with HILTI® HUS3-H8 concrete anchors @ 500 c/c.
 4. The top vertical gap provided in the DST was 24 mm.
 5. The studs at the ends of the walls were boxed 64 × 35 × 0.5 mm studs with 100 × 58 × 32 mm timber planks placed at the ends.
 6. The other studs were 64 × 35 ×0.5 mm lipped wall studs spaced @ 500 mm c/c.
 7. The 63 × 63 × 3 mm aluminium angles were fixed to the DSTs at the ends and junctions of the walls with four tek-screws
 8. The aluminium angles were covered by gypsum strips (notched at ends) screwed to the end-studs
 9. The vertical joint gaps between the plasterboards at the junctions were filled with (HILTI®-400 Fire) sealant and covered by paper tape mimicking wallpaper for aesthetics.
 10. partition wall specimens (1875 height, 2200 length)
ds_description: paper-tape strechmarks

specimen: Rocking DST detail with sacrificial L-trim joints
design_objective:
seismic performance of “rocking” internal
 partition walls with the dual-slot track (DST) and aluminium angles, with Concealed Joints
comp_description:
1. The cold-formed steel framing consisted of dual-slot track (DST) constructed by tek-screwing 64 × 45 × 0.5 mm inner track to 92 × 26 × 0.5 mm outer track, 64 × 35 × 0.5 mm studs @ 600 mm c/c, and 64 × 32 × 0.75 mm nogging tracks.
 2. Additional 13 mm thick plasterboard strips were placed between the concrete slabs and DST at the top and bottom of the partition wall.
 3. The DSTs were then anchored to the concrete slabs with HILTI® HUS3-H M8 concrete anchors.
 4. The nogging tracks were screwed to the studs but were discontinuous at the locations of the vertical joints
 5. GIB® standard 13 mm thick plasterboard panels were placed in the slot of the DSTs and were screwed only to the studs.
 6. 50×50×3 mm aluminium angles were placed at the ends of the wall specimen and vertical joints between the plasterboard panels by tek-screwing the angles using 2–10 gauge wafer head screws to the
 DST
 7. A full-scale partition wall specimen was constructed between two parallel concrete slabs supported by steel frames. Height: 3400 mm, Length: 3000mm
 8. Joint detail: comprised of two GIB® paper-faced external 90-degree metal trims (L-trims) covering a 6 mm horizontal joint width provided at the junctions of plasterboard panels. These L-trims are bedded in three layers of jointing compound (two layers/coats of GIB® 45 mins Trade set and one final layer of multi GIB®Trade finish) applied at the vertical joint
ds_description: Plaster cracks between adjacent plasterboard panels

design_objective: seismic performance assessment of internal partition walls with novel slotted and bracketed head-track details
comp_description:
1. L-shaped Full-scale partition wall specimens with slotted head-tracks: Height 1875mm, Length (1813 mm x 926 mm)
 2. The cold-formed steel framing consisted of 64 × 32 × 0.5 mm tracks, 64 × 35 × 0.5 mm studs, and 64 × 32 × 0.75 mm nogging tracks from STUDCO
 3. The off-cuts from the studs were used as braces.
 4. The 150 mm x 12 mm slots in the head tracks. The concrete anchor with a long shank (Pring 2020) that passes through the slot into the concrete
 5. The spacing between the top anchors provided track flexibility to “bow” in and out during the out-ofplane lateral drifts
 6. The “L” junction comprised one stud from the in-plane wall (L1) and three studs from the transverse wall (L2), where two studs faced each other, forming a box.
 7. The internal frame was sheathed with 13 mm GIB® standard plasterboards/panels
 8. The plasterboards were connected to the internal steel frame using 25 mm × 6 g GIB® Drywall Self Tapping Screws at 300 mm c/c except at the boundaries where the spacing was kept at 150 mm c/c.
 9.The joints were then plastered with two coats of GIB® Tradeset 90-minute premium jointing compound, jointing tape, and internal and external corner beads (/L-trims).
 10. steel frame and gypsum plasterboard connected to steel tracks
ds_description: Slight damage to gypsum plasterboards and fire seal

design_objective: seismic performance assessment of internal partition walls with novel slotted and bracketed head-track details
comp_description:
1. Y-shaped Full-scale partition wall specimens with slotted head-tracks and Flexibrackets: Height 1875mm, Length of wing walls (1474 mmx 536 mm x 601mm)
 2. “L” junction (in the west end) and a Y-junction (in the east end).
 3. The steel framing consisted of 64 × 32 × 0.5 mm tracks, 64 × 35 × 0.5 mm studs, and braces, 64 × 32 × 0.5 mm nogging tracks from FRAMECAD®
 4. All the frame members were connected using tek screws at the provided holes
 5. The 150 mm x12 mm slots in the head tracks of the return walls (Y2 and Y3) and the inclined wall (Y4) were cut manually at the ends
 6. The bottom track was anchored to the concrete slab using the HUS3 anchors.
 7. the top track was bolted (finger-tight) to the Flexibrackets at the slots. Then, the brackets were anchored to the concrete slab above. The Flexibracket (Pring 2021) has a C-shape, with 180° curved ends. It is made of Simona® SIMOLIFE PE flex low-density polyethylene (LDPE) plastic.
ds_description: No Damage

design_objective: effect of the cladding presence upon the lateral resistance of the frame to be investigated
comp_description:
1. Full-bay, singlestorey panel (L=3775mm, H=2975mm, 120mm thick; window size: L=2005mm, H=1615mm)
2. Had a central, single opening where a window would normally be located. 
3. contained a single layer of reinforcement in each direction.The panels are reinforced with D12’s at 200 mm centres and D16 bars around the opening and external perimeter. 1.0 m length D16s also run diagonally at each corner opening
4. A 28 day concrete compressive strength of 40 MPa was specified for the panels. Grade
300 steel was used for reinforcement.
5. Metal angles were used as the bearing connections and were bolted into place using two M20 ferrule anchors cast into the panel and frame.
6. The panel connections were designed according to the requirements for parts and
components of NZS 1170.5 (2004).
7. long threaded rod connections: rod size = 20mm, number of connection =2, exposed length of the rods was 250 mm, Fixed-fixed ends, Steel Grade= 4.6
ds_description:
visible cracks parallel to the threads of the threaded rods were observed in
between the threads

design_objective: effect of the cladding presence upon the lateral resistance of the frame to be investigated
comp_description:
1. Full-bay, singlestorey panel (L=3775mm, H=2975mm, 120mm thick; window size: L=2005mm, H=1615mm)
2. Had a central, single opening where a window would normally be located. 
3. contained a single layer of reinforcement in each direction.The panels are reinforced with D12’s at 200 mm centres and D16 bars around the opening and external perimeter. 1.0 m length D16s also run diagonally at each corner opening
4. A 28 day concrete compressive strength of 40 MPa was specified for the panels. Grade
300 steel was used for reinforcement.
5. Metal angles were used as the bearing connections and were bolted into place using two M20 ferrule anchors cast into the panel and frame.
6. The panel connections were designed according to the requirements for parts and
components of NZS 1170.5 (2004).
7. short threaded rod connections:  two mild steel rods of 20 mm diameter connecting the cladding panel to the underside of the beam. The exposed length of the rods was 50 mm.
13. short threaded rod connections: Rod size=4x 20mm, Number of locations=2, Mild steel; Fixed-fixed ends
ds_description: Localised cracking in the threaded rods

design_objective:
to determine if an optimal configuration existed, as well as to discover possible drawbacks from using the
connections
comp_description:
Configuration 1 corresponds to the RHS housing being fixed to the panel with the slot
facing outwards with the movement occurring between this outside face of the housing and
the metal angle on the underside of the beam.
1. Full-bay, singlestorey panel (L=3775mm, H=2975mm, 120mm thick; window size: L=2005mm, H=1615mm)
2. Had a central, single opening where a window would normally be located. 
3. contained a single layer of reinforcement in each direction.The panels are reinforced with D12’s at 200 mm centres and D16 bars around the opening and external perimeter. 1.0 m length D16s also run diagonally at each corner opening
4. A 28 day concrete compressive strength of 40 MPa was specified for the panels. Grade
300 steel was used for reinforcement.
5. The precast concrete panels were attached to the frame using two different connection
types: bearing connections and UFP connections. The bearing connections located at the
base of the panels, and the UFP connections were located at the top of the panel.
6. The UFP connections were bolted to the underside of the top beams using 300 mm long
t-channels that were cast into the concrete.
7. The connection to the panels made use of the 10 mm thick steel plates secured to the panel with four cast-in ferrule anchors. 
8. Including housed and unhoused UFPs as well as the UFPs in different orientations.
9. No of connections = 2 (2UFPs), UnHoused
10 UFP is 8 mm thick, 120 mm wide Grade 300 steel plate. The fabricator of the UFPs was a local spring maker who heated the plates prior to bending. Each UFP was bent around a fixed diameter of 120 mm.
ds_description:
out-of-plane movement
of the panel being unacceptable

comp_description:
Configuration 1 corresponds to the RHS housing being fixed to the panel with the slot
facing outwards with the movement occurring between this outside face of the housing and
the metal angle on the underside of the beam.
1. Full-bay, singlestorey panel (L=3775mm, H=2975mm, 120mm thick; window size: L=2005mm, H=1615mm)
2. Had a central, single opening where a window would normally be located. 
3. contained a single layer of reinforcement in each direction.The panels are reinforced with D12’s at 200 mm centres and D16 bars around the opening and external perimeter. 1.0 m length D16s also run diagonally at each corner opening
4. A 28 day concrete compressive strength of 40 MPa was specified for the panels. Grade
300 steel was used for reinforcement.
5. The precast concrete panels were attached to the frame using two different connection
types: bearing connections and UFP connections. The bearing connections located at the
base of the panels, and the UFP connections were located at the top of the panel.
6. The UFP connections were bolted to the underside of the top beams using 300 mm long
t-channels that were cast into the concrete.
7. The connection to the panels made use of the 10 mm thick steel plates secured to the panel with four cast-in ferrule anchors. 
8. Including housed and unhoused UFPs as well as the UFPs in different orientations.
9. No of connections = 4 (4UFPs), Housed
10. slotted connections were attached to the top of the panel to provide out-of-plane restraint
11. UFP is 8 mm thick, 120 mm wide Grade 300 steel plate. The fabricator of the UFPs was a local spring maker who heated the plates prior to bending. Each UFP was bent around a fixed diameter of 120 mm.
ds_description: No Damage

ds_description:
the doors at the lower three levels sustained severe damage when averaged PIDR demands were extremely large (6% at the lower two levels and 3.5% at level 3). The gaps
 between the doors at levels 2 and 3 reached a maximum residual of 200 mm at their base (Figure 7(b)), and corner crushing of the elevator doors progressed as a result of severe interaction between the doors and the partition walls (Figure 7(c)). The damaged doors eventually resulted in inoperability of the elevator and loss of compartmentation in the case of post-earthquake fire

loading_protocol: The loading protocols with gradually increasing peak displacements as recommended by ANSI/AISC 341-16 for the qualifying cyclic tests of the beam-to-column moment connections in special and intermediate moment frames
design_objective:
experimentally demonstrate
 the benefits of the new exterior wall system with steel
 tapered - tee energy absorbers installed between two adjacent panels
comp_description:
1.a single-story frame (2m high x 3.3 m wide) in which two precast panels and six identical steel tee energy absorbers were installed.
 2. precast panel: 200-mm thick, 1100-mm wide, and 2500-mm high.
 3. doubly reinforced as a one-way slab using the steel bars with the nominal diameter of 8 mm
 4. the precast wall panel was also locally reinforced over the segments close to the bolt holes using the steel bars with the nominal diameter of 8 mm. 
 5. All the steel bars had the same nominal yield strength of 400 MPa.
 6. the widths of the wide and narrow ends of the tee web, denoted as bw and bn, were kept constant at 200 mm and 18 mm
 7. the length of the web segment inserted in to the gap between two adjacent restrainers was kept constant at 24 mm.
 8. Properties of Tee-connector: tw=10mm, lw=120mm, r=24mm, tf=15mm, tr=16 mm, td=15 mm, hot rolled steel
ds_description: No Damage
notes:
After Phase I test, cracks and concrete
 cover peeling-off were observed in the one of the panels (not sure which specimen). The damage
 essentially concentrated in the region around the lower panel-to-beam
 connector where the inelastic strains may have concentrated due to
 the transfer of the gravity load of the entire panel to the bottom beam of
 the frame.

loading_protocol:
Protocol II consists of constant displacement amplitudes of
 ±40 mm repeated ten times.
location:
Laboratorio Prove e Materiali of Politecnico
 di Milano, Italy
design_objective:
investigate the behaviour of both single devices and groups of joint connections when subjected to sliding
 between concrete panels
comp_description:
1. It consists of of two solid concrete panels 129 cm large, 323 cm long and 16 cm thick, with aspect ratio equal to 2,50.
 2. The panels are provided with a top vertical slot at mid-width for the installation of the panel-to-beam connection, with a distance from the bottom panel-to-foundation connection to the top panel-to-beam connection of 280 cm.
 3. The base panel connection is made with a pin inserted into a steel fork bolted to sockets embedded into the panel and to the foundation beam.
 4. The top panel connections are made of passing round holes hosting steel pins that connect the panels to the steel articulated frame that transmits the imposed displacements to the panels.
 5. The recesses in the panels have been designed in order to accommodate the FBDs made with symmetric T-shaped profiles and class 10.9 M14 bolts provided with Belleville washers.
 6. Number of connections = 1
ds_description: No Damage
notes:
Friction Based Devices (FBDs) are mechanical connections
 inserted into appropriate recesses within the joints between vertical
 or horizontal concrete panels. The FBD is made by three elements assembled through bolts.

peak_test_amplitude:
Peak Acceleration of Table (g)
 a. Parallel to the flat panel = 0.36g
 b. Perpendicular to the flat panel =0.26g
comp_description:
1. Two full-scale precast concrete cladding panels were tested on the exterior face of a full-scale 5-story steel frame building. two full-height column cover panels were designed and built.
 2. The precast cladding panels were designed according to common U.S. practice
 3. The tall-narrow panels are designed to accommodate inter-story drift in a complex, rocking motion
 4. Vertical gravity load (U2 local axis direction) is transferred from the panel to the structural frame through the bottom connections where the panel connection uses a leveling bolt which sits on a preweld assembly cantilevered from the main structural frame members.
 5. The top connection is detailed to provide horizontal resistance (U1 local axis direction) to prevent the panel from falling from the building.
 6. Separating these two panels is a vertical seismic joint that allows independent motion of the two panels 
 7. No sealant joint between the panels.
ds_description: No Damage

1. sub-assemblies of four ‘rocking’ panels (in a 2 × 2 grid) with interposed sealant joints along the vertical and horizontal interfaces were subjected to lateral cyclic loadings on a small-scale two-story 3D structural frame
 2. 929mm high x 1015 mm wide x 125 mm thick panels
 3. 25 mm joint widths filled with sealant; sealant cured only for 9 days
 4.Vertical slots connection at four corners in the panel with 21 mm slot length
 5. two Bearing plates embedded at the bottom corners of the panels for gravity load transfer
ds_description: Adhesive failure of the sealant in horizontal joint

loading_protocol: a synthetic earthquake ground motion was used. The synthetic earthquake ground motion was modulated from the record of Landers earthquake in 1992.
design_objective: Chinese Q/GDW11132-2013
comp_description:
The porcelain bushing was mounted
in a copper flange, and the porcelain bushing and flange were connected by cement. To
transmit the electrical current, an aluminum central conductor was installed in the bushing.
A terminal pad was installed at the top of the bushing to connect the conductor. Besides, a
grading ring was mounted on the bushing to maintain the electromagnetic field around
the terminal pad, and SF6 insulating gas were filled in the bushing for internal insulation,
with an air pressure of 0.45 MPa. The total length of the porcelain bushing is 12.475 m,
with a length of the porcelain part of 10.5 m. The total weight of the porcelain bushing
is 6300 kg, and the location of the centre of gravity is distanced to the flange with 4.45 m.

loading_protocol: a synthetic earthquake ground motion was used. The synthetic earthquake ground motion was modulated from the record of Landers earthquake in 1992.
design_objective: Chinese Q/GDW11132-2013
comp_description:
The polymer composite bushing is shown in Figure 1b. The total length of the composite bushing is 12.27 m, and the length of the composite polymer composite insulator is
11.25 m. Similar to the porcelain counterpart, the polymer composite insulator is installed in
an aluminum flange, and a central conductor is installed in the insulator, with a 0.5-MPa air
pressure SF6. To increase the outer insulating distance, the sheds made by silicone rubber
are set around the outer surface of the GFRP composite insulator. The inner and outer
diameters of the composite bushing are 1000 mm and 1048 mm, respectively. Moreover,
the total weight of the composite bushing is 4400 kg, and the centre of gravity is a 5.6 m
distance to the flange.

comp_description:
Full-scale fire sprinkler piping system, Concrete floor, beams and columns,  steel pipes, pressurized, Riser and the main pipe: groove fit,
other joints: threaded, No ceiling interaction, Braced according to NFPA-13 (2010)
ds_description: Tearing of Fire-stopping
proir_damage: displacement of mineral wool at penetrations

loading_protocol:
The floor motions used were recorded during 2010/11 Canterbury Eqs on an eight-story RC building, UC Physics at the University of Canterbury

One random moton generated to match the target spectrum in AC156
peak_test_amplitude:
All motions were initially scaled to a peak acceleration of 0.1g.
These motions were then input to the table with scale factors
of 1.0, 1.5, 3.0, 4.5, 6.0, 7.5 and 8.5. The maximum capacity
of the table, 1.0g,
comp_description:
Plenum depth: Main pipe: 39 in. (1000 mm), Branch pipe: 16 – 18 in. (400-450 mm)
steel pipes, Steel columns and beam, concrete sections for brace and hanger connections, 
Pressure: 175 psi (1.2 MPa),No riser, main and branch pipe connected using a 600mm long riser nipple with Victaulic Mechanical-T outlet (threaded)
other joints: threaded, Braces to main pipes include 25 mm (1.0 in) schedule 40 steel pipes.
No ceiling interaction, irrespective of pipe diameters
ds_description: No damage

test_type: Uniaxial shake table (ground) motions that were artificially generated by using a spectrum-matching procedure
loading_protocol:
Parameters from the AC 156 [ICC, 2010] including, a story height ratio (z/h) of 0.5 and the design spectral 
response acceleration at short periods (SDS) of 2.5 g, were used to develop two targeted acceleration spectrum
location:
University of Nevada, Reno Network for Earthquake Engineering Simulation
site
comp_description:
Pressure = 50 psi
Riser pipe = 4 in diameter
Branch pipe= 2 in diameter (update if necessary)
armovers=1 in diameter
Plenum depth varied from 12 in to 22 in
Hangers = 10mm (3/8 in) dia threaded rods
Braces = 1 in schedule 40 pipes oriented at 45 degrees
Wire restrainers(splay wires) = 12 g wires @ 45 degrees
Braces and Wire restrainers connected to concrete deck through 10 mm (3/8 in) Hilti KB-TZ expansion anchors
The gap between the sprinkler hed and ceiling tile was either 2 in or no gap. 
The ceiling system looks like braced.
ds_description: Longitudinal brace connections to pipes slip off
